<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
This species was clearly described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Sutcharit, C" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" refId="B83" refString="Sutcharit, C, Lin, A, Panha, S, 2020. Two new species of the carnivorous snail genus Discartemon from Thailand and Myanmar (Eupulmonata: Streptaxidae). The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology (Supplement No. 35): 149-155." title="Two new species of the carnivorous snail genus Discartemon from Thailand and Myanmar (Eupulmonata: Streptaxidae). The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology (Supplement No. 35): 149 - 155." year="2020">Sutcharit et al. (2020)</bibRefCitation>
. Shell is depressed-heliciform, white and translucent, spire low conical to convex with wide and depressed suture. Shell surface glossy, with fine transverse ridges that diminish below periphery; varices present. Embryonic shell large, ~ 
<normalizedToken originalValue="2½">21/2</normalizedToken>
whorls with smooth surface; following whorls in regularly expanding coil. Last whorl usually angular; widely open umbilicus. Apertural dentition with one strong parietal, one palatal, one basal, one columellar and one supracolumellar lamella (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. A, B Discartemon tonywhitteni, specimen CUMZ 6264 from Phra (Buddha) Cave, Tanintharyi Region C-E Discartemon paurodeviatus sp. nov. C holotype CUMZ 13002 with apertural dentition and D, E paratypes CUMZ 13003 from the type locality." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1110.85399.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/710468" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">3A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Genital organs</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Atrium (at) short. Penis (p) long and slender. Penial sheath (ps) thin and extending ~1/2 to 3/4 of penis length; penial sheath retractor muscle (psr) very thin, originating at atrium and inserting distally on penial sheath (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Genital anatomy of A, B Discartemon tonywhitteni, specimen CUMZ 13001 A reproductive system and B insertion of vas deferens into penial sheath C, D Discartemon paurodeviatus sp. nov., paratype CUMZ 13003 C reproductive system and D insertion of vas deferens into penial sheath." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1110.85399.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/710469" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4A</figureCitation>
). Vas deferens (vd) very short, ~ 1/6 of penial sheath length and passes through penial sheath before entering penis distally (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Genital anatomy of A, B Discartemon tonywhitteni, specimen CUMZ 13001 A reproductive system and B insertion of vas deferens into penial sheath C, D Discartemon paurodeviatus sp. nov., paratype CUMZ 13003 C reproductive system and D insertion of vas deferens into penial sheath." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1110.85399.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/710469" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4B</figureCitation>
). Penial retractor muscle (pr) thin and very long, inserting at penis and vas deferens junction.
</paragraph>
